<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-755-491  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 755 491.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Dec 20 1990 v16 n26 p9(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Serving multiple platforms: software. (Julius da Costa, NationalSales Mgr, Ventura Software Inc.) (In Conversation) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>da Costa, Julius.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The multiple-platform environment is the main challenge that facesthe software industry at the present time.andP;  Decreasing hardwarecosts are tending to decentralize purchasing decisions, so thatindividual departments rather than monolithic MIS operations aredetermining corporate platforms.andP;  As a result, the successfulsoftware vendor will be the one that bases its strategy upon thegoal of serving multiple platforms.andP;  In the present environment,decision makers are not inclined to make exclusive investments toeither DOS, OS/2, Windows or any other operating system.andP;  Successin today's software market means being prepared to implementsolutions for multiple platforms; it demands the flexibility toprovide programs that are appropriate for each customer's hardwareand software requirements.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ventura Software Inc. (Management).andO;Topic:     ManagementSoftware PublishersNetwork Operating SystemsMultiuser SoftwareUser NeedsOutlook.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Julius da Costa. (portrait)Person:    da Costa, Julius (Attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Serving multiple platformsandM;SOFTWAREandM;Every software vendor must deal with multiple-platform environments.andP;  Withhardware prices dropping and demand for computers growing, control bydecentralized Information Systems organizations has yielded to ad hocdepartment level purchasing decisions.andP;  The idea is to give workers computingpower at their desktops.andM;Personal computing pundits might have you believe that there is awinner-take-all battle going on for platform performance.andP;  In the area of PCsoftware, for instance, the long-time DOS standard was challenged by OS/2followed by a resurgence of interest in Windows.andP;  But it is important tofirst dispense of the mythology of &quot;battles&quot; and &quot;either/or choices.&quot;andM;DOS, Windows, OS/2 and Macintosh will all have substantial corporate userbases for years to come.andP;  Simply stated: DOS was right and will continue tobe right in the global PC market for some time, DOS/Windows and Macintosh areright and OS/2-PM will be right.andP;  In addition, workstation products from Sun,DEC, IBM and Hewlett-Packard are important platforms.andP;  These products usecost-effective, high-performance, RISC architectures in conjunction with Unixto offer an alternative.andM;Many corporate decision makers are wary of committing prematurely to a nextgeneration OS/2 standard.andP;  They see many users who are not seriously hamperedby the 640K memory limit of DOS, and are content with their XT and earlyAT-level PCs.andP;  Windows has some appeal to these users as a low-risk upgradethat does not threaten the application software status quo.andM;But most PC users as yet have no clear idea of how the true multi-platformtasking capabilities of OS/2 and Unix will benefit them.andP;  Many are quitesatisfied for now with concurrent access to multiple applications offered byWindows 3.0.andM;There is a growing understanding of the value of multi-tasking and workgroupcomputing; and of the technical superiority of OS/2 and Unix for officeautomation and information/image management.andM;Satisfying customer needs in this multi-platform world poses considerablechallenges to software companies.andP;  It is important to support the DOScommunity which remains very large and loyal.andP;  Yet it is not easy to addfunctional value to a technically limited platform and incremental softwareupgrades do not produce viabile new products.andM;There is no single, perfect solution for every user.andP;  Multiple platforms willprevail and desktop software suppliers must bring solutions to customers onthe platforms of their choice.andO;</TEXT></DOC>